The chicken embryo chorioallantoic membrane test (CAM) represents a conventional approach for assessing the potential irritation of samples. Fresh eggs with weights ranging from 50 to 60 g were selected for the study [32]. The incubation environment consisted of a temperature of 37.5 ± 0.5 °C and humidity levels between 60% and 70%. The orientation of the air chambers was adjusted to facilitate upwards opening, after which the cells were incubated for a period of nine to eleven days. A volume of 300 µL of the positive control solution (0.1 mol/L NaOH), negative control solution (0.9% NaCl), unfermented A. cochinchinensis solution (0.6 mg/mL) or fermented A. cochinchinensis solution (0.6 mg/mL) was applied directly onto the surface of the CAM. The CAM reaction was monitored, and the intervals of haemorrhage, coagulation, and vascular dissolution were documented within a five-minute period. To ascertain the efficacy of the test, the sample was evaluated in six parallel sets, with the reaction time method employed for the assessment. The formula provided below was used to compute the stimulus score, which is identified as the IS.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
