The red blood cell haemolysis test was used to assess the potential irritation of the samples. This experiment used 0.4% sodium dodecyl sulphate (SDS) as the positive control and PBS as the negative control [33]. The samples were assessed at concentrations ranging from 0.2 to 1 mg/mL. A total of 0.5 mL of red blood cell (RBC) suspension was added to 1.5 mL of test solution, and the mixture was incubated for 30 min at 37 °C in a shaker. Following incubation, the mixture was subjected to centrifugation at 10,000 rpm for a period of 2 min. The resulting supernatant was collected, and the absorbance values for each sample were quantified at a wavelength of 560 nm via a microplate reader. The haemolysis ratio was calculated via the following equation:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
